<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-689-242  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 689 242.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Iandamp;CS (Instrumentation andamp; Control Systems)  August 1989 v62 n8p57(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber optics extend the reach of photoelectric sensors.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McHugh, Pete.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The rapid growth of fiber optic photoelectronic sensors to 15percent of 1989's $150 million photoelectronic sensor market (witha 30 percent share projected by the mid 1990s) is a consequence ofthe variety, flexibility of fiber optic cables and sensoramplifiers, and decreasing costs.andP;  Fiber optic sensor amplifierscan fit in small spaces, detect small objects, are immune to manyharsh environments, and offer reliable output.andP;  The sensors areavailable in ac and dc versions, offer digital and analog outputs,and handle through-beam, retro-reflective, and diffuse sensingmodes.andP;  Fiber optic cables are highly durable, suitable for mostharsh environments, immune to electromagnetic and radio frequencyinterferences, and the compact size is suitable for tight spaces.andO;Developments in analog output fiber optic sensors are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsCablesOptoelectronic DevicesSystem DesignSensorsApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   The two basic styles of fiber optic assemblies. (chart)Applications of special fiber optic cables. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>